To count the number of lines in a file, you can use the `wc` command in most Unix-like systems, as follows:

```
wc -l filename.txt 
```

Replace `filename.txt` with your actual file name.
This will give you the number of lines (`-l`) in the specified file.
The `-l` option tells `wc` to only display the line count.
The `-l` option stands for "lines" and it will output the number of lines in your file.
The output will display the number of lines, to the left of the word "lines".
The `-l` option tells `wc` to only print the line count.
This will output the number of lines in the file.

If you're on Windows and don't have access to Unix commands, you can open the file in Notepad++ (or any other text editor that shows line numbers) and look at the bottom right corner of the window, the line number shown is the total number of lines in the file.

Alternatively, to get only the line count, to view easily, you can do 

```
wc -l < filename.txt 
```

If you're using Windows, to view the contents of the file (i.e., "cat" the file), you can type:

```
type filename.txt 
```

But if you want to count the number of lines in Windows, to do so, you'd need to pipe the output to a tool like `find` or `findstr`, for example:

```
type filename.txt | find /c "$"
```

This will count the number of lines by counting the occurrences of the end-of-line character (`$`).

Alternatively, to view the contents of the file and count the lines simultaneously, to do that you can use:

```
cat filename.txt | wc -l 
```
